{"id":"2206.00365","submitter":"Florian Bo{\\ss}mann","authors":"Florian Bossmann and Jianwei Ma","title":"ORKA: Object reconstruction using a K-approximation graph","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Inverse Problems 38 125009, 2022","doi":"10.1088/1361-6420/aca046","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Data processing has to deal with many practical difficulties. Data is often\ncorrupted by artifacts or noise and acquiring data can be expensive and\ndifficult. Thus, the given data is often incomplete and inaccurate. To overcome\nthese problems, it is often assumed that the data is sparse or low-dimensional\nin some domain. When multiple measurements are taken, this sparsity often\nappears in a structured manner. We propose a new model that assumes the data\nonly contains a few relevant objects, i.e., it is sparse in some object domain.\nWe model an object as a structure that can only change slightly in form and\ncontinuously in position over different measurements. This can be modeled by a\nmatrix with highly correlated columns and a column shift operator that we\nintroduce in this work. We present an efficient algorithm to solve the object\nreconstruction problem based on a K-approximation graph. We prove optimal\napproximation bounds and perform a numerical evaluation of the method. Examples\nfrom applications including Geophysics, video processing, and others will be\ngiven.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Jun 2022 10:04:06 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 27 Sep 2022 06:00:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-18"}
